"Generate a complete testing suite for the LendHand Loan Management System. Include unit tests, integration tests, and end-to-end (E2E) tests for all key modules and user workflows. Use the following guidelines:

General Guidelines

Language/Frameworks: Java 17, Spring Boot backend, JUnit 5 for unit & integration tests, Mockito for mocking, and Selenium or Cypress for E2E front-end tests.

Testing Levels:

Unit Tests: Test individual methods, services, and utilities in isolation. Include boundary cases, exceptions, and edge scenarios.

Integration Tests: Test service layers with database interactions and API endpoints. Use in-memory DB (H2) for testing.

E2E Tests: Test full user workflows in web portal and Android app (if possible, simulate mobile actions). Cover main workflows for Owner, Cashier, and Borrower.

Modules & Features to Cover

Borrower Module

Registration & profile creation

KYC document upload & validation

Blacklist checking

Loan Application Module

Application submission & validation

Automated risk assessment

Document attachment

Loan Approval & Disbursement Module

Owner approval/rejection workflows

Repayment schedule generation

Disbursement recording

Repayment Module

Payment recording (full, partial, late payments)

Balance recalculation

Notification sending

Reporting & Analytics Module

Dashboard metrics calculation

Performance & aging reports

Risk assessment summary

Security & Authentication

JWT authentication

Role-based access control

Sensitive data encryption validation

Testing Requirements

Generate mock data where necessary

Include positive and negative test cases

Use assertions to validate expected behavior

Include comments describing each test

Structure tests in a maintainable folder structure (unit, integration, E2E)

Output Format

For Java backend: JUnit 5 classes with methods for each test case

For frontend: Selenium/Cypress scripts for main workflows

Include a README for running all tests with Maven/Gradle commands

Ensure that the generated tests can be run independently and collectively to verify system correctness."